00:10:18,960 --> 00:10:20,280
Lady, that's back
over the mouth.

273
00:10:20,320 --> 00:10:22,680
I'm headed to Lincoln,
about two hours away.

274
00:10:22,720 --> 00:10:24,120
Take it or leave it.

275
00:10:24,160 --> 00:10:26,960
What, I can't even ride
in the back of the truck?

276
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,240
No honor among
hitchhikers anymore.

277
00:10:29,280 --> 00:10:30,800
Might as well take the damn bus.

278
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:35,800
What's that over there?

279
00:10:35,840 --> 00:10:37,240
That's the Lincoln steel mill.

280
00:10:37,280 --> 00:10:38,360
We're coming into town now.

281
00:11:01,880 --> 00:11:02,760
Thanks a lot.

282
00:11:19,480 --> 00:11:20,400
Oh, dear.

283
00:11:20,440 --> 00:11:21,760
Mommy, is that a bag lady?

284
00:11:26,680 --> 00:11:28,040
Good morning.

285
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:28,840
Morning.

286
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:55,040
He picked up his spare.

287
00:11:55,080 --> 00:11:56,600
Ooh, Joycee, he's on fire.

288
00:11:56,640 --> 00:11:57,880
What's he at?

289
00:11:57,920 --> 00:11:59,440
He's gonna nail a
650 series, for sure.

290
00:11:59,480 --> 00:12:00,320
Who's this?

291
00:12:04,760 --> 00:12:08,960
She could bowl in
our bag lady league.

292
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:10,560
Answering machine.

293
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:12,760
It's 4:00 in the morning in LA.

294
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:14,240
Fran, it's me.

295
00:12:14,280 --> 00:12:16,000
Don't call out the National
Guard, I'm all right.

296
00:12:16,040 --> 00:12:18,160
But don't tell Harry or Ryan.

297
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:20,560
Tell them that I am
lost and feared dead.

298
00:12:20,600 --> 00:12:22,280
Actually, don't tell--
don't tell Harry that.

299
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:24,080
He'll get Glenn Close.

300
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:25,840
I'm coming home.

301
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:27,160
I've got to, um--

302
00:12:27,200 --> 00:12:29,120
actually, I can't come home.

303
00:12:29,160 --> 00:12:30,480
I need to get money.

304
00:12:30,520 --> 00:12:32,520
You've got to get Fred
to wire me some money.

305
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:33,840
I'm in, um--

306
00:12:33,880 --> 00:12:36,920
I don't know what the
hell this place is.

307
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:39,320
I can't read the number
on the telephone.

308
00:12:39,360 --> 00:12:40,560
So I'll call you back.
Never mind.

309
00:12:40,600 --> 00:12:41,400
Bye.

310
00:12:45,080 --> 00:12:48,280
Get the money up front.

311
00:12:48,320 --> 00:12:49,640
Coffee?

312
00:12:49,680 --> 00:12:51,720
- Yes, please.
- Cream and sugar?

313
00:12:51,760 --> 00:12:53,120
Just a little cream.

314
00:12:57,200 --> 00:13:00,920
It's 7:00 in the
morning, who's bowling?

315
00:13:00,960 --> 00:13:03,440
That's the Midnight Humpers
versus the Dawn Patrol.

316
00:13:03,480 --> 00:13:04,720
The Midnight Humpers?

317
00:13:04,760 --> 00:13:05,880
Yeah.

318
00:13:05,920 --> 00:13:07,200
It's the guys coming
off the midnight

319
00:13:07,240 --> 00:13:08,400
shift at the mill
against the guys

320
00:13:08,440 --> 00:13:09,920
coming on the 8 o'clock shift.

321
00:13:09,960 --> 00:13:11,720
They've got an hour
off, and they're bowling?

322
00:13:11,760 --> 00:13:12,720
Are you kidding?

323
00:13:12,760 --> 00:13:14,000
These guys bowl in their sleep.

324
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:15,200
They bowl for their
wedding receptions.

325
00:13:15,240 --> 00:13:18,200
We've got a bar mitzvah bowl.

326
00:13:18,240 --> 00:13:19,800
I'm in bowl hell.

327
00:13:19,840 --> 00:13:21,640
Can I ask you a question?

328
00:13:21,680 --> 00:13:23,320
Shoot.

329
00:13:23,360 --> 00:13:25,440
What are these weird
things behind me?

330
00:13:25,480 --> 00:13:27,040
You mean the bowlers?

331
00:13:27,080 --> 00:13:29,120
No, I mean the skinny
pins and the tiny balls.

332
00:13:29,160 --> 00:13:30,000
Oh.

333
00:13:30,040 --> 00:13:30,920
Candlepin.

334
00:13:30,960 --> 00:13:32,400
It's an east coast thing.

335
00:13:32,440 --> 00:13:34,440
It's English.

336
00:13:34,480 --> 00:13:37,240
Can I get you anything else?

337
00:13:37,280 --> 00:13:38,840
A plane ticket out of here.

338
00:13:38,880 --> 00:13:43,160
Did I mention that
I have no money?

339
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:44,680
The coffee I can
get you on the house,

340
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:46,120
but you're on your own
for the plane ticket.

341
00:13:46,160 --> 00:13:47,000
Thank you.

342
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:52,440
You in some kind of trouble?

343
00:13:52,480 --> 00:13:55,600
Now, why would you think that?

344
00:13:55,640 --> 00:13:57,680
You want to talk about it.

345
00:13:57,720 --> 00:13:58,640
No.

346
00:13:58,680 --> 00:14:00,000
OK.

347
00:14:00,040 --> 00:14:01,360
You can use the phone
in the office for free.

348
00:14:06,800 --> 00:14:07,600
I don't know who I'd call.

349
00:14:11,040 --> 00:14:13,480
That's trouble, all right.

350
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:17,360
Look, um, for starters, how
about I loan you some clothes?

351
00:14:17,400 --> 00:14:18,480
You would loan me clothes?

352
00:14:18,520 --> 00:14:21,080
Why would you loan me clothes?

353
00:14:21,120 --> 00:14:23,280
Because you need them.

354
00:14:23,320 --> 00:14:24,120
Joycee.

355
00:14:28,640 --> 00:14:29,600
Get rid of her.

356
00:14:29,640 --> 00:14:31,040
She's a bag lady.

357
00:14:31,080 --> 00:14:33,520
She's not a bag lady.

358
00:14:33,560 --> 00:14:34,480
She's broke.

359
00:14:34,520 --> 00:14:36,240
She's wearing baggy clothes.

360
00:14:36,280 --> 00:14:37,800
She's a bag lady.

361
00:14:37,840 --> 00:14:38,760
It's a new look.

362
00:14:38,800 --> 00:14:41,640
It's that Elizabethan thing.

363
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:44,040
OK, we are RSVPed yes to
the Streisand-Lockett party--

364
00:14:44,080 --> 00:14:45,200
Fran.

365
00:14:45,240 --> 00:14:46,440
--no to the
Thanksgiving Day Parade?

366
00:14:46,480 --> 00:14:47,400
Who were they kidding?

367
00:14:47,440 --> 00:14:48,840
Fran, listen--

368
00:14:48,880 --> 00:14:50,080
And a maybe to the Ozone
Replenishment Benefit.

369
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:51,320
- Fran, Sydney called.
- What?

370
00:14:51,360 --> 00:14:52,760
Yeah, she left a message.

371
00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:53,760
She doesn't know the name
of the town she's in.

372
00:14:53,800 --> 00:14:55,360
She doesn't have any money.

373
00:14:55,400 --> 00:14:56,840
And she didn't know the number
that she was calling from.

374
00:14:56,880 --> 00:14:58,480
But she's going to call back.
- Oh, that's insane.

375
00:14:58,520 --> 00:15:00,040
- So what's new?
- OK, zip it.

376
00:15:00,080 --> 00:15:01,760
Get me Harry on the phone,
and then get me the studio.

377
00:15:01,800 --> 00:15:03,200
No, no, Harry already called.

378
00:15:03,240 --> 00:15:04,440
He knew she was there, was
because some gas station

379
00:15:04,480 --> 00:15:05,560
attendant saw her
with a truck driver.

380
00:15:05,600 --> 00:15:07,720
A truck driver?

381
00:15:07,760 --> 00:15:09,240
For her?
- I'll call the studio.

382
00:15:09,280 --> 00:15:10,040
Yeah.

383
00:15:25,840 --> 00:15:28,960
Anyone ever tell you, you
look like Sandra Bullock?

384
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:31,160
I don't think I look
anything like Sandra Bullock.

385
00:15:31,200 --> 00:15:32,800
Hmm.

386
00:15:32,840 --> 00:15:35,800
Well, her, or a little bit like
that actress, Sydney Clarke.

387
00:15:35,840 --> 00:15:38,400
Except for the blond hair
and those poofy lips.

388
00:15:38,440 --> 00:15:40,000
She had them injected
with sheep fat, you know?

389
00:15:40,040 --> 00:15:41,480
Oh, she did not.

390
00:15:41,520 --> 00:15:42,960
I read it in a magazine.

391
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,160
It's true.

392
00:15:45,200 --> 00:15:47,320
So what is your name?

393
00:15:47,360 --> 00:15:48,640
Uh, Cheryl.

394
00:15:48,680 --> 00:15:49,760
Cheryl Belson.

395
00:15:49,800 --> 00:15:50,920
Well, it's nice
to meet you, Cheryl.

396
00:15:50,960 --> 00:15:51,800
I'm Joyce McMurphy.

397
00:15:51,840 --> 00:15:52,800
You, too.

398
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:54,480
Cheryl, promise me one thing.

399
00:15:54,520 --> 00:15:55,880
What?

400
00:15:55,920 --> 00:15:58,920
That one day you'll
tell me about that dress,

401
00:15:58,960 --> 00:16:00,000
and the last couple of days.

402
00:16:00,040 --> 00:16:02,760
It's a long story, but I will.

403
00:16:02,800 --> 00:16:04,640
WALTER: I don't know what
you're doing in there, Joycee,

404
00:16:04,680 --> 00:16:05,560
but we're backed up out here!

405
00:16:05,600 --> 00:16:06,400
Come on.

406
00:16:09,440 --> 00:16:10,920
Only cook it once, kiddo.

407
00:16:10,960 --> 00:16:12,080
I know, I know.

408
00:16:12,120 --> 00:16:13,080
All cooks are the same.

409
00:16:13,120 --> 00:16:14,160
A persnickety group of people.

410
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:16,160
Cheryl, hold your arm up.

411
00:16:16,200 --> 00:16:17,160
Palms up.

412
00:16:17,200 --> 00:16:18,280
Thank you.

413
00:16:18,320 --> 00:16:19,640
Well, what--
what are you doing?

414
00:16:19,680 --> 00:16:20,800
Do me a favor, run
this down to lane three.

415
00:16:20,840 --> 00:16:21,680
Me?

416
00:16:21,720 --> 00:16:22,800
Oh, I don't think so.

417
00:16:22,840 --> 00:16:24,160
What's your problem?

418
00:16:24,200 --> 00:16:25,400
You're asking
me to wait tables?

419
00:16:25,440 --> 00:16:27,360
No, I'm asking you
to do me a favor.

420
00:16:27,400 --> 00:16:29,080
How's a person supposed
to carry all this?

421
00:16:29,120 --> 00:16:30,200
Haven't you ever
heard of a tray?

422
00:16:30,240 --> 00:16:31,880
Yeah, sure.

423
00:16:31,920 --> 00:16:33,680
There you go.
- OK.

424
00:16:33,720 --> 00:16:34,920
Go, lane three.

425
00:16:34,960 --> 00:16:36,240
Lose the attitude,
you might get a tip.

426
00:16:39,680 --> 00:16:40,800
Yes!

427
00:16:40,840 --> 00:16:43,200
Ha ha, see ya later.

428
00:16:43,240 --> 00:16:44,680
See ya later, buddy.

429
00:16:44,720 --> 00:16:46,600
Can somebody give
me a hand, please?

430
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:48,040
Save my drink!
Save my--

431
00:16:48,080 --> 00:16:49,000
Hang on, we got them.

432
00:16:49,040 --> 00:16:49,920
We got them.

433
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:52,880
Oh, thank you.

434
00:16:52,920 --> 00:16:53,880
How much we owe you?

435
00:16:53,920 --> 00:16:54,760
I don't know.

436
00:16:54,800 --> 00:16:57,360
I'm not a waitress.

437
00:16:57,400 --> 00:16:59,360
Well, that's apparent.

438
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:00,360
Hey, Joyce!

439
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:01,280
How much?

440
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:04,120
Uh, $10.50.

441
00:17:04,160 --> 00:17:09,760
Ten, fifty.

442
00:17:09,800 --> 00:17:12,920
Ah, the Bill Gates of bowling.

443
00:17:12,960 --> 00:17:15,200
Tipping is not a city
in China, you know?

444
00:17:15,240 --> 00:17:16,160
That's good.

445
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:18,400
Thank you, Peaches.

446
00:17:18,440 --> 00:17:20,280
Cheryl, and I'm
leaving tomorrow.

447
00:17:20,320 --> 00:17:22,680
- I wasn't asking.
- Yes, you were.

448
00:17:22,720 --> 00:17:25,080
What's your hurry?

449
00:17:25,120 --> 00:17:26,400
Hard to make a living here.

450
00:17:26,440 --> 00:17:28,000
You're telling me.

451
00:17:28,040 --> 00:17:29,400
Maybe you're in the
wrong line of work.

452
00:17:29,440 --> 00:17:31,280
You got that right.

453
00:17:31,320 --> 00:17:32,520
So stick around anyway.

454
00:17:32,560 --> 00:17:33,600
Now, why would
I want to do that?

455
00:17:36,840 --> 00:17:38,640
Because I'm here.

456
00:17:38,680 --> 00:17:41,520
That's why I'm leaving.

457
00:17:41,560 --> 00:17:42,560
Youch!

458
00:17:42,600 --> 00:17:44,400
Chewed him up and spit him out.

459
00:17:44,440 --> 00:17:45,400
That hurt.

460
00:17:45,440 --> 00:17:46,520
Total annihilation, brother.

461
00:17:46,560 --> 00:17:47,480
Yeah, you want
to know something?

462
00:17:47,520 --> 00:17:48,480
She really likes me.

463
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:49,400
Yeah.

464
00:17:49,440 --> 00:17:50,200
Oh, yeah.

465
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:03,520
Lot of houses for sale.

466
00:18:03,560 --> 00:18:04,960
Well, people are scared.

467
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:06,160
Every time there's another
rumor about the mill

468
00:18:06,200 --> 00:18:07,600
closing, somebody leaves

469
00:18:07,640 --> 00:18:08,960
- Lock up, will you, Joycee?
- Sure, no problem.

470
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:10,640
Good night, Walter.
- Thanks.

471
00:18:10,680 --> 00:18:12,160
You don't mind if I hang here
until the rain stops, do you?

472
00:18:12,200 --> 00:18:13,480
No, not at all.

473
00:18:13,520 --> 00:18:15,280
Um, but can you give
me a hand, or are you

474
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:16,800
going to stand there
like the Queen of England

475
00:18:16,840 --> 00:18:18,040
and watch me drop this stuff?
- Sure.

476
00:18:18,080 --> 00:18:20,800
What do you need me to do.

477
00:18:20,840 --> 00:18:22,080
I'm just kidding ya.

478
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:24,720
Here, take this,
push A1 on the jukebox.

479
00:18:24,760 --> 00:18:26,160
Ooh, I can handle that.

480
00:18:26,200 --> 00:18:27,400
Good.

481
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:29,040
So where are you from, Cheryl.

482
00:18:29,080 --> 00:18:30,040
Mississippi.

483
00:18:30,080 --> 00:18:31,040
Pushmataha.

484
00:18:31,080 --> 00:18:33,680
I thought I heard an accent.

485
00:18:33,720 --> 00:18:35,960
How did you wind up here?

486
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:38,040
Sort of walked off a job.

487
00:18:38,080 --> 00:18:39,920
That's a hell of a long walk.
[music from jukebox]

488
00:18:39,960 --> 00:18:40,800
Oh!

489
00:18:40,840 --> 00:18:42,280
I used to love this song!

490
00:18:42,320 --> 00:18:43,920
Yeah, me, too.

491
00:18:43,960 --> 00:18:45,640
Every time we heard this song,
we had to jitterbug to this.

492
00:18:45,680 --> 00:18:47,120
- Oh, yeah?
- Ooh, come dance with me.

493
00:18:47,160 --> 00:18:48,200
- Cut it out.
- Oh, come on.

494
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:49,320
Put that down.

495
00:18:49,360 --> 00:18:51,440
Whoo!

496
00:18:51,480 --> 00:18:52,800
I don't do this very well.

497
00:18:57,280 --> 00:19:03,280
BOTH: [singing] I'll always
love you, always love you.

498
00:19:03,320 --> 00:19:04,360
- Get ready now.
- What?

499
00:19:04,400 --> 00:19:05,240
Whoo!

500
00:19:05,280 --> 00:19:06,160
Ah!

501
00:19:06,200 --> 00:19:08,160
[crashing sounds]

502
00:19:15,720 --> 00:19:17,680
I'll get my crutches.

503
00:19:17,720 --> 00:19:18,960
Hang on!

504
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:20,120
Wait, wait, wait,
don't move without me.

505
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:20,880
- I'm fine.
- Just a second.

506
00:19:20,920 --> 00:19:22,280
I'm fine.
Ow!

507
00:19:22,320 --> 00:19:24,280
- Oh, Joyce, I'm so sorry.
- It's OK.

508
00:19:24,320 --> 00:19:25,320
I just bumped it.
- Are you OK?

509
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:26,360
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

510
00:19:26,400 --> 00:19:28,200
Just grab my bag.
Thank you.

511
00:19:28,240 --> 00:19:29,160
All right, take it easy.

512
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:30,040
Slow!

513
00:19:30,080 --> 00:19:31,040
Joyce, wait a second.

514
00:19:31,080 --> 00:19:32,400
I've got it.
I've got it.

515
00:19:32,440 --> 00:19:33,760
Have you got it?

516
00:19:33,800 --> 00:19:34,880
I can't remember when
I've had so much fun.

517
00:19:34,920 --> 00:19:36,120
I'm so sorry.

518
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:37,520
If you say you're
sorry one more time,

519
00:19:37,560 --> 00:19:39,960
I will whack you, OK?

520
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:41,200
Easy.

521
00:19:41,240 --> 00:19:42,720
So where you going
to stay tonight?

522
00:19:42,760 --> 00:19:44,200
I haven't figured
that out yet.

523
00:19:44,240 --> 00:19:46,720
Well, you're welcome
to stay on my couch.

524
00:19:46,760 --> 00:19:48,080
Joyce, you're
such a nice person.

525
00:19:48,120 --> 00:19:49,400
I don't know what to make of it.

526
00:19:49,440 --> 00:19:51,400
Are you sure you're
not southern?

527
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:53,560
If that means thank
you, you're welcome.

528
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:54,480
Door's unlocked.

529
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:55,600
No, we don't lock it.

530
00:19:55,640 --> 00:19:56,920
Oh, small town.

531
00:19:56,960 --> 00:19:57,720
I love it.

532
00:20:16,560 --> 00:20:18,560
How do you feel?

533
00:20:18,600 --> 00:20:19,400
I'll live.

534
00:20:23,320 --> 00:20:24,200
Can I see that?
- Sure.

535
00:20:24,240 --> 00:20:25,040
Thanks.

536
00:20:27,960 --> 00:20:30,800
That is so good.

537
00:20:30,840 --> 00:20:32,160
Thank you.

538
00:20:32,200 --> 00:20:34,560
Is that what you do
back in Pushmahooha?

539
00:20:34,600 --> 00:20:36,360
Pushmataha.

540
00:20:36,400 --> 00:20:37,480
No.

541
00:20:37,520 --> 00:20:40,280
Worked at a tropical fish store.

542
00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:41,440
That's the job
you walked out on?

543
00:20:41,480 --> 00:20:44,160
The guppies got to you, huh?

544
00:20:44,200 --> 00:20:48,560
No, the piranhas, not to
mention a cheating fiance.

545
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:50,760
Ouch.

546
00:20:50,800 --> 00:20:52,400
So now what'll you do?

547
00:20:52,440 --> 00:20:55,360
I mean, what would you like
to do if you had your choice?

548
00:20:55,400 --> 00:20:58,480
Ooh, what a question.

549
00:20:58,520 --> 00:21:00,000
If I could do anything,
what would I do?

550
00:21:03,360 --> 00:21:06,560
36 years old, and I don't
know the answer to that.

551
00:21:06,600 --> 00:21:08,200
Can I give you
a little advice?

552
00:21:08,240 --> 00:21:09,800
Sure.

553
00:21:09,840 --> 00:21:12,160
I don't think you're quite
cut out to wait tables.

554
00:21:12,200 --> 00:21:13,600
No kidding.

555
00:21:13,640 --> 00:21:16,080
I like my food brought to
me, thank you very much.

556
00:21:16,120 --> 00:21:17,600
What about you?

557
00:21:17,640 --> 00:21:19,080
You gonna hang out with
the Midnight Humpers

558
00:21:19,120 --> 00:21:21,080
the rest of your life?
- No, actually.

559
00:21:21,120 --> 00:21:23,640
Someday I'd like to open up a
little cafe down by the lake,

560
00:21:23,680 --> 00:21:25,200
own my own business.

561
00:21:25,240 --> 00:21:26,480
What a wonderful idea.

562
00:21:26,520 --> 00:21:28,200
Why don't you do that?

563
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:29,520
Risky.

564
00:21:29,560 --> 00:21:31,160
Mill closes down, so
does everything else.

565
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:34,520
Well, risks are meant
to be taken, right?

566
00:21:34,560 --> 00:21:37,640
Well, one step at
a time, if I'm lucky.

567
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:39,400
First, I gotta figure
out how to wait

568
00:21:39,440 --> 00:21:42,760
tables walking on my hands.

569
00:21:42,800 --> 00:21:45,200
I gotta figure out how to
get out of here, no offense.

570
00:21:45,240 --> 00:21:47,480
Where is the
nearest big airport?

571
00:21:47,520 --> 00:21:49,040
Boston.

572
00:21:49,080 --> 00:21:50,920
OK, I have friends in Boston.

573
00:21:50,960 --> 00:21:51,840
How do I get to Boston?

574
00:21:51,880 --> 00:21:52,760
Do I take a train, bus?

575
00:21:52,800 --> 00:21:53,680
What?

576
00:21:53,720 --> 00:21:55,040
We got a train station.

577
00:21:55,080 --> 00:21:57,560
Train leaves tonight, I
think around 8 o'clock.

578
00:21:57,600 --> 00:22:01,120
Oh, I just have
one little problem.

579
00:22:01,160 --> 00:22:01,920
Oh.

580
00:22:05,360 --> 00:22:06,680
Joyce, I don't know
how to thank you.

581
00:22:06,720 --> 00:22:07,640
Would you stop it?

582
00:22:07,680 --> 00:22:09,360
Just keep it.

583
00:22:09,400 --> 00:22:10,760
I practically
break your foot off,

584
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:12,440
and you lend me a
week's worth of tips.

585
00:22:12,480 --> 00:22:14,600
Cheryl, the way I was
raised, somebody needs

586
00:22:14,640 --> 00:22:15,600
help, you give it to them.

587
00:22:15,640 --> 00:22:16,600
You'll pay me back.

588
00:22:16,640 --> 00:22:17,760
You've got my address.
- Sure.

589
00:22:17,800 --> 00:22:19,120
Thank you.

590
00:22:19,160 --> 00:22:20,560
I'll get your clothes
back to you right away.

591
00:22:20,600 --> 00:22:21,760
Promise.

592
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:24,240
Did I mention the
interest payments?

593
00:22:24,280 --> 00:22:25,680
I gotta get back to work.

594
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:26,960
Thank you so much.

595
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:28,680
I'll be in touch.

596
00:22:28,720 --> 00:22:29,760
You take care.

597
00:22:29,800 --> 00:22:31,280
Yeah, you, too.

598
00:22:31,320 --> 00:22:32,160
See ya.

599
00:22:32,200 --> 00:22:33,000
Bye.

600
00:22:49,760 --> 00:22:53,640
This train should
be here any minute.

601
00:22:53,680 --> 00:22:55,200
Where you heading?

602
00:22:55,240 --> 00:22:57,640
Not me.

603
00:22:57,680 --> 00:22:58,600
My daughter's coming home.

604
00:22:58,640 --> 00:22:59,920
Oh, that's nice.

605
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:01,680
Yeah.

606
00:23:01,720 --> 00:23:06,080
Yeah, she's 33 now.

607
00:23:06,120 --> 00:23:08,680
I haven't seen her
for almost four years.

608
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:15,520
Nothing's better
than coming home.

609
00:23:15,560 --> 00:23:17,160
She must have
traveled a lot, huh?

610
00:23:17,200 --> 00:23:19,280
Oh, there's been
a place or two.

611
00:23:22,960 --> 00:23:32,640
Greece, the island of
Crete, Italy, Switzerland.

612
00:23:32,680 --> 00:23:35,520
Well, most of Europe, really.

613
00:23:35,560 --> 00:23:39,680
England, as far up as Norway.

614
00:23:39,720 --> 00:23:43,200
Oh, that's not counting the
Arctics, both up and down.

615
00:23:43,240 --> 00:23:46,080
It sounds adventurous.

616
00:23:46,120 --> 00:23:49,880
She went everywhere.

617
00:23:49,920 --> 00:23:54,000
But the best place is home,
where people love you,

618
00:23:54,040 --> 00:23:55,040
where they care about you.

619
00:23:59,520 --> 00:24:02,000
Well, she's home.

620
00:24:04,960 --> 00:24:05,760
Enjoy the visit.

621
00:24:15,280 --> 00:24:16,120
Oh, my god.

622
00:24:36,040 --> 00:24:37,760
Otis and Kirby, order's up!

623
00:24:37,800 --> 00:24:41,080
Come get it!

624
00:24:41,120 --> 00:24:42,920
There you go.

625
00:24:42,960 --> 00:24:44,360
Tell you what, Kirby.

626
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:46,320
I'll carry yours,
you carry mine.

627
00:24:46,360 --> 00:24:48,800
That way, it'll still feel
like someone brung it to us.

628
00:24:48,840 --> 00:24:49,640
Good idea.

629
00:24:52,440 --> 00:24:54,160
Very funny, boys.

630
00:24:54,200 --> 00:24:55,640
Two Stooges of bowling.

631
00:24:55,680 --> 00:24:56,480
She's back.

632
00:25:01,680 --> 00:25:03,440
Fran, you're never there.

633
00:25:03,480 --> 00:25:05,520
It's Sydney.

634
00:25:05,560 --> 00:25:08,560
Listen, I'm not going
to come back right away.

635
00:25:08,600 --> 00:25:11,720
I gotta-- I gotta--

636
00:25:11,760 --> 00:25:12,720
I don't know what I gotta do.

637
00:25:12,760 --> 00:25:13,840
Something.

638
00:25:13,880 --> 00:25:17,000
I'll-- I'll call
you in a few days.

639
00:25:17,040 --> 00:25:17,840
Bye.

640
00:25:31,640 --> 00:25:32,680
Hey.

641
00:25:32,720 --> 00:25:34,000
Hey.

642
00:25:34,040 --> 00:25:36,200
You all right?

643
00:25:36,240 --> 00:25:37,960
I don't know.

644
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:41,120
I thought you were going home.

645
00:25:41,160 --> 00:25:44,680
Right now, here seems
better than there.

646
00:25:44,720 --> 00:25:47,520
OK.

647
00:25:47,560 --> 00:25:49,400
Well, what are we going
to do with you, then?

648
00:25:49,440 --> 00:25:51,040
Besides fish food,
what have you done?

649
00:25:51,080 --> 00:25:52,840
What have I done?

650
00:25:52,880 --> 00:25:54,040
You mean work?

651
00:25:54,080 --> 00:25:55,360
Yeah, work.

652
00:25:55,400 --> 00:25:57,520
I think we've exhausted
the waitress thing.

653
00:25:57,560 --> 00:26:00,400
Yeah.

654
00:26:00,440 --> 00:26:02,840
Well, I've-- I've
done a lot of things.

655
00:26:02,880 --> 00:26:04,440
When I was a teenager,
I flipped burgers.

656
00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:05,600
Mm-hmm.

657
00:26:05,640 --> 00:26:10,200
I was a nurse's
aid once, sort of.

658
00:26:10,240 --> 00:26:13,920
That's how you knew
to put ice on my foot.

659
00:26:13,960 --> 00:26:15,200
Yeah.

660
00:26:15,240 --> 00:26:17,440
I tell you what, my
friend, Darlene, is

661
00:26:17,480 --> 00:26:19,680
the nurse at the
mill, and she is dying

662
00:26:19,720 --> 00:26:21,360
to visit her sister in Florida.

663
00:26:21,400 --> 00:26:22,680
Oh, I don't know.

664
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:24,880
You could cover for
her during her vacation.

665
00:26:24,920 --> 00:26:26,080
The pay's pretty good.

666
00:26:26,120 --> 00:26:27,120
I can't do that.

667
00:26:27,160 --> 00:26:28,480
Just till she gets back.

668
00:26:28,520 --> 00:26:30,000
Look, it'll put
money in your pocket,

669
00:26:30,040 --> 00:26:31,120
get your confidence back.

670
00:26:31,160 --> 00:26:32,840
I'm going to set
it up right now.

671
00:26:32,880 --> 00:26:34,120
All you gotta do is
turn on the boss.

672
00:26:34,160 --> 00:26:35,280
Gonna get along great.

673
00:26:40,040 --> 00:26:41,480
I know we have to
make this shipment,

674
00:26:41,520 --> 00:26:43,320
but I can't speed it up
without slacking on safety,

675
00:26:43,360 --> 00:26:46,480
and I'm not going to do that.

676
00:26:46,520 --> 00:26:48,040
Mr. Cameron?

677
00:26:48,080 --> 00:26:49,880
Peaches.

678
00:26:49,920 --> 00:26:51,960
Well, I thought you
were leaving town.

679
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:53,520
- You're the boss?
- Yeah.

680
00:26:53,560 --> 00:26:54,600
Ben, remember?

681
00:26:54,640 --> 00:26:56,520
Yeah.

682
00:26:56,560 --> 00:26:58,200
Wow, a waitress, now a nurse.

683
00:26:58,240 --> 00:27:00,440
If this keeps up, you'll be
mayor by the end of the week.

684
00:27:00,480 --> 00:27:02,720
Huh, Belson.

685
00:27:02,760 --> 00:27:05,120
Mississippi.

686
00:27:05,160 --> 00:27:06,360
Pushma--

687
00:27:06,400 --> 00:27:09,080
Pushmataha.

688
00:27:09,120 --> 00:27:11,920
You know, I never actually met
anyone from Mississippi before.

689
00:27:11,960 --> 00:27:13,160
Yeah?

690
00:27:13,200 --> 00:27:15,360
Well, most of us are
wearing shoes now.

691
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:16,640
We got indoor plumbing, too.

692
00:27:19,880 --> 00:27:22,760
You look very familiar.

693
00:27:22,800 --> 00:27:24,840
Huh.

694
00:27:24,880 --> 00:27:26,440
Let's see.

695
00:27:26,480 --> 00:27:27,400
Work history.

696
00:27:27,440 --> 00:27:29,360
Sold tropical fish supplies.

697
00:27:29,400 --> 00:27:31,200
Gourmet chef.

698
00:27:31,240 --> 00:27:32,640
Part time nurse.

699
00:27:32,680 --> 00:27:34,520
Well, actually, it was
more like a nurse's aide.

700
00:27:34,560 --> 00:27:36,400
Well, how are
you with splinters?

701
00:27:36,440 --> 00:27:38,360
That's about as serious
as it gets around here.

702
00:27:38,400 --> 00:27:40,280
Of course, there was that
one time that Guy Helier got

703
00:27:40,320 --> 00:27:42,760
decapitated with
a hydraulic drill.

704
00:27:42,800 --> 00:27:45,360
You're kidding, right?

705
00:27:45,400 --> 00:27:47,040
Yeah.

706
00:27:47,080 --> 00:27:48,120
Very funny.

707
00:27:48,160 --> 00:27:51,160
Steel mill humor?

708
00:27:51,200 --> 00:27:52,120
You're hired.

709
00:27:52,160 --> 00:27:53,040
Just like that?

710
00:27:53,080 --> 00:27:54,480
Steel mill intuition.

711
00:27:54,520 --> 00:27:59,240
You got a certain big
city something about you.

712
00:27:59,280 --> 00:28:00,600
But not entirely.

713
00:28:00,640 --> 00:28:02,160
I like it.

714
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:04,840
I thought you were leaving town.

715
00:28:04,880 --> 00:28:06,040
I thought so, too.

716
00:28:06,080 --> 00:28:08,240
Well, lucky for us.

717
00:28:08,280 --> 00:28:11,360
Come on, Peaches,
I'll show you around.

718
00:28:11,400 --> 00:28:14,720
The mill has six divisions,
deploying over 1,000 men.

719
00:28:14,760 --> 00:28:16,240
This division makes
steel products,

720
00:28:16,280 --> 00:28:17,480
bridges, stuff like that.

721
00:28:17,520 --> 00:28:19,000
Mm-hmm.

722
00:28:19,040 --> 00:28:20,840
My grandfather helped
build this place in the '20s.

723
00:28:20,880 --> 00:28:22,280
- Did he really?
- Yeah.

724
00:28:22,320 --> 00:28:23,680
The town was really
prosperous then.

725
00:28:23,720 --> 00:28:26,520
Well, it seems
busy enough now.

726
00:28:26,560 --> 00:28:28,200
Well, what you're
seeing are guys

727
00:28:28,240 --> 00:28:31,440
working double shifts in order
to keep the mill in the black.

728
00:28:31,480 --> 00:28:33,000
It's what everybody
has to do these days

729
00:28:33,040 --> 00:28:34,720
to compete with foreign steel.

730
00:28:34,760 --> 00:28:38,080
The nurse's station and the
lunch room are up there.

731
00:28:51,480 --> 00:28:53,040
Dick, this is Cheryl Belson.

732
00:28:53,080 --> 00:28:54,360
She'll be taking over for
Darlene until she comes back.

733
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:55,680
Hi.
Nice to meet you.

734
00:28:55,720 --> 00:28:56,840
Very nice to meet you.

735
00:28:56,880 --> 00:28:58,440
Welcome.

736
00:28:58,480 --> 00:28:59,840
- Can you give us a second?
- Oh, sure.

737
00:28:59,880 --> 00:29:00,760
No problem.

738
00:29:00,800 --> 00:29:02,480
Thank you.

739
00:29:02,520 --> 00:29:05,760
Ben, did you, uh-- did you send
in that report to New York yet?

740
00:29:05,800 --> 00:29:07,560
No, I was hoping the output
would improve this week,

741
00:29:07,600 --> 00:29:09,000
so I can send something
more optimistic.

742
00:29:09,040 --> 00:29:10,440
Why?
- Good.

743
00:29:10,480 --> 00:29:11,920
Because I wanted to go to
the accounts receivable

744
00:29:11,960 --> 00:29:13,560
and see if I can shake loose
a few dollars from some

745
00:29:13,600 --> 00:29:15,640
of these guys that owe to us,
you know, and tip the numbers

746
00:29:15,680 --> 00:29:17,640
in our favor a little bit?

747
00:29:17,680 --> 00:29:18,840
- OK.
- Good.

748
00:29:18,880 --> 00:29:19,720
Great.

749
00:29:19,760 --> 00:29:22,520
Hey, Dick, everything OK?

750
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:23,440
I just got a call.

751
00:29:23,480 --> 00:29:24,840
Elaine fell again.

752
00:29:24,880 --> 00:29:25,760
That's my wife.

753
00:29:25,800 --> 00:29:28,040
She's been pretty sick.

754
00:29:28,080 --> 00:29:29,880
- Is she all right?
- Well, nothing's broke.

755
00:29:29,920 --> 00:29:32,200
But I can't say she's OK.

756
00:29:32,240 --> 00:29:34,000
It's been a pretty tough
go for the last two years.

757
00:29:34,040 --> 00:29:35,600
She's getting tired.

758
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:36,640
Well, what are you doing here?

759
00:29:36,680 --> 00:29:37,560
Go be with her.

760
00:29:37,600 --> 00:29:38,720
Oh, I can't do that.

761
00:29:38,760 --> 00:29:39,960
You know what's on my desk.

762
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:41,400
Look, If I need
you, I'll call you.

763
00:29:41,440 --> 00:29:42,560
Go ahead.

764
00:29:42,600 --> 00:29:44,240
Go!

765
00:29:44,280 --> 00:29:45,080
Thanks, Ben.

766
00:29:49,120 --> 00:29:50,880
That was a nice thing to do.

767
00:29:50,920 --> 00:29:53,480
Well, I'm a nice guy.

768
00:29:53,520 --> 00:29:55,240
A lot of people I know
who wouldn't have done that.

769
00:29:55,280 --> 00:29:57,240
It sounds like you're hanging
out with the wrong crowd.

770
00:29:57,280 --> 00:29:58,080
Here's your office.

771
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:06,680
What do you think?

772
00:30:06,720 --> 00:30:08,480
Looks like home to me.

773
00:30:08,520 --> 00:30:09,720
SYDNEY CLARKE [ON
ANSWERING MACHINE]:

774
00:30:09,760 --> 00:30:10,720
I don't know what I got to do.

775
00:30:10,760 --> 00:30:11,640
Something.

776
00:30:11,680 --> 00:30:12,840
I'll call you in a few days.

777
00:30:12,880 --> 00:30:15,400
Bye.

778
00:30:15,440 --> 00:30:16,880
In a few days.

779
00:30:16,920 --> 00:30:18,480
Get me the studio.

780
00:30:18,520 --> 00:30:19,880
Executives are going to be
hemorrhaging all over the lot.

781
00:30:19,920 --> 00:30:22,840
Ryan's on two, and
your mom's still on hold.

782
00:30:22,880 --> 00:30:26,640
Mom, hold on.
Ryan?

783
00:30:26,680 --> 00:30:28,600
Oh, of course, she's coming.

784
00:30:28,640 --> 00:30:31,120
I talked to Sydney this morning.

785
00:30:31,160 --> 00:30:33,560
Everything will be fine.

786
00:30:33,600 --> 00:30:34,720
You, too.

787
00:30:34,760 --> 00:30:35,560
Kiss, kiss.

788
00:30:38,480 --> 00:30:40,440
I don't see any
splinters, Otis.

789
00:30:40,480 --> 00:30:42,280
I don't know,
I felt something.

790
00:30:42,320 --> 00:30:44,080
A metal filing, maybe?

791
00:30:44,120 --> 00:30:44,920
Let me get some aspirin.

792
00:30:51,880 --> 00:30:54,040
You can go back to work now.

793
00:30:54,080 --> 00:30:57,320
Well, what about checking
out that splinter in my butt?

794
00:30:57,360 --> 00:30:58,600
Sit on a mirror and
check it yourself.

795
00:31:02,960 --> 00:31:04,880
Sit on a mirror the
check it yourself?

796
00:31:04,920 --> 00:31:05,920
What kind of nurse is that?

797
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:09,600
Yeah!

798
00:31:13,720 --> 00:31:15,880
Ow.

799
00:31:15,920 --> 00:31:16,720
Come on in.

800
00:31:19,760 --> 00:31:20,720
Hey.

801
00:31:20,760 --> 00:31:22,480
You think about my idea?

802
00:31:22,520 --> 00:31:23,960
Ben, it doesn't work.

803
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:25,280
Guys doing these jobs, they
don't make enough money

804
00:31:25,320 --> 00:31:26,640
to buy back the plant.

805
00:31:26,680 --> 00:31:28,960
Hey, John, I need that
mig gun by tomorrow!

806
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:31,160
Where do you come up with
these Wall Street strategies?

807
00:31:31,200 --> 00:31:32,840
Well, we got to do something.

808
00:31:32,880 --> 00:31:34,400
Relax, brother, they've been
threatening to close this place

809
00:31:34,440 --> 00:31:35,680
down since we were kids.

810
00:31:35,720 --> 00:31:37,360
Yeah, well, this
time it might happen.

811
00:31:37,400 --> 00:31:39,400
Look, just because they shut
down Ithaca doesn't mean we're

812
00:31:39,440 --> 00:31:40,880
going down, too.

813
00:31:40,920 --> 00:31:42,360
Hey, you saved New Bedford,
you'll save us as well.

814
00:31:42,400 --> 00:31:43,520
Stop worrying.

815
00:31:43,560 --> 00:31:44,400
Yeah.

816
00:31:44,440 --> 00:31:45,880
Hey, Ben, hit me long.

817
00:31:55,880 --> 00:31:57,320
Nice hands, Jimmy!

818
00:31:57,360 --> 00:31:59,120
Nice arm.

819
00:31:59,160 --> 00:32:00,080
You must have played.

820
00:32:00,120 --> 00:32:01,640
What, in college?

821
00:32:01,680 --> 00:32:02,840
A little bit.

822
00:32:02,880 --> 00:32:04,640
Where did he play?

823
00:32:04,680 --> 00:32:06,680
As a nurse, what would
you prescribe for him?

824
00:32:06,720 --> 00:32:07,480
Stick to bowling.

825
00:32:10,400 --> 00:32:13,160
So uh, how is your
first day going so far?

826
00:32:13,200 --> 00:32:15,280
Lot of aches and
pains, twisted ankle.

827
00:32:15,320 --> 00:32:16,800
Drew the line at
checking for hernias.

828
00:32:16,840 --> 00:32:18,120
Smart.

829
00:32:18,160 --> 00:32:19,560
So what are you going
to do to celebrate?

830
00:32:19,600 --> 00:32:20,440
Celebrate?

831
00:32:20,480 --> 00:32:21,800
Yeah, you got a new job.

832
00:32:21,840 --> 00:32:24,160
A person gets a new job,
they ought to celebrate.

833
00:32:24,200 --> 00:32:25,960
I don't have anything
planned, really.

834
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:28,560
Well, in that case, how
about dinner at my house?

835
00:32:28,600 --> 00:32:30,440
You don't quit, do you?

836
00:32:30,480 --> 00:32:32,320
Well, I haven't
heard you say no.

837
00:32:32,360 --> 00:32:33,480
And if I did?

838
00:32:33,520 --> 00:32:34,840
I'd be perfectly fine with it.

839
00:32:34,880 --> 00:32:35,720
Nah, I don't think so.

840
00:32:35,760 --> 00:32:36,600
Come on!

841
00:32:36,640 --> 00:32:39,080
You just got a new job!

842
00:32:39,120 --> 00:32:42,200
Ah, it's very sweet of
you, I just don't think so.

843
00:32:42,240 --> 00:32:43,840
Oh, how do you say
I don't think so.

844
00:32:43,880 --> 00:32:44,760
It's impossible.

845
00:32:44,800 --> 00:32:46,440
Just say yes.

846
00:32:46,480 --> 00:32:47,640
Come on, just yes.

847
00:32:47,680 --> 00:32:49,160
A simple yes.
What else you gonna do?

848
00:32:49,200 --> 00:32:50,240
Who do-- what else you gonna do?

849
00:32:50,280 --> 00:32:52,880
Who do you know in town?

850
00:32:52,920 --> 00:32:53,800
OK.

851
00:32:53,840 --> 00:32:55,480
All right, already.

852
00:32:55,520 --> 00:32:58,320
As long as I don't have to carry
more than one plate at a time.

853
00:32:58,360 --> 00:33:01,000
Actually, I was
hoping you'd cook.

854
00:33:01,040 --> 00:33:02,360
I have to cook?

855
00:33:02,400 --> 00:33:05,880
Well, your resume says
you're a gourmet chef.

856
00:33:05,920 --> 00:33:08,000
Besides, I got a couple of
trout I caught yesterday.

857
00:33:08,040 --> 00:33:11,680
It needs a little loving
hand, a little imagination,

858
00:33:11,720 --> 00:33:13,440
culinary skill.

859
00:33:13,480 --> 00:33:15,400
Where do you live?

860
00:33:15,440 --> 00:33:17,560
I'm staying at Joyce's.

861
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:19,480
Really?

862
00:33:19,520 --> 00:33:21,080
Well, uh, I'll pick
you up at 7:00.

863
00:33:21,120 --> 00:33:22,000
OK.

864
00:33:22,040 --> 00:33:23,080
See ya at 7:00.

865
00:33:23,120 --> 00:33:23,880
Great.

866
00:33:28,960 --> 00:33:31,160
I just don't understand how
you could tell him you were

867
00:33:31,200 --> 00:33:32,760
a chef when you really weren't.

868
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:34,080
Well, I wasn't lying.

869
00:33:34,120 --> 00:33:35,920
I just didn't stick
with it for very long.

870
00:33:35,960 --> 00:33:37,920
Oh.

871
00:33:37,960 --> 00:33:40,080
You like him, don't you?

872
00:33:40,120 --> 00:33:41,880
Maybe.

873
00:33:41,920 --> 00:33:44,560
You want to try
this-- ravishing red?

874
00:33:44,600 --> 00:33:45,880
Sure, I guess.

875
00:33:45,920 --> 00:33:47,160
I mean, I've never
done them before.

876
00:33:47,200 --> 00:33:49,000
You've never done
your nails before?

877
00:33:49,040 --> 00:33:50,040
In this color.

878
00:33:50,080 --> 00:33:52,440
Oh.

879
00:33:52,480 --> 00:33:53,840
Hey, this one might work--

880
00:33:53,880 --> 00:33:55,960
flambe the trout.

881
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:57,000
Simplemente to flambe.

882
00:33:57,040 --> 00:33:58,560
Ooh-la-la.

883
00:33:58,600 --> 00:34:02,320
And for your nails, I have
the perfect color sweater.

884
00:34:02,360 --> 00:34:03,800
[doorbell ringing]

885
00:34:03,840 --> 00:34:05,200
Oh, that's probably Carter.

886
00:34:05,240 --> 00:34:07,760
Here you go.

887
00:34:07,800 --> 00:34:08,680
Hi.

888
00:34:08,720 --> 00:34:09,680
Hi.

889
00:34:09,720 --> 00:34:10,760
- How are you?
- Good.

890
00:34:10,800 --> 00:34:11,640
How are you?

891
00:34:11,680 --> 00:34:12,560
I'm OK.

892
00:34:17,120 --> 00:34:19,760
Ah, the boyfriend.

893
00:34:19,800 --> 00:34:21,240
Carter, this is Cheryl Belson.

894
00:34:21,280 --> 00:34:23,880
She's visiting from
somewhere in Mississippi.

895
00:34:23,920 --> 00:34:24,760
This is Carter.

896
00:34:24,800 --> 00:34:26,200
Yes, the boyfriend.

897
00:34:26,240 --> 00:34:27,600
It's so nice to
meet you, Carter.

898
00:34:27,640 --> 00:34:29,080
Likewise.

899
00:34:29,120 --> 00:34:32,360
She is a bit like
Sidney Clarke, but, uh,

900
00:34:32,400 --> 00:34:34,480
Sydney is a little more zaftig.

901
00:34:34,520 --> 00:34:35,560
Zaftig?

902
00:34:35,600 --> 00:34:37,000
It means chunky.

903
00:34:37,040 --> 00:34:38,720
I know what it means.

904
00:34:38,760 --> 00:34:40,960
Carter's the director
of our community theater.

905
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:42,200
Oh, how nice.

906
00:34:42,240 --> 00:34:44,800
Mmm, I'm holding
auditions next week,

907
00:34:44,840 --> 00:34:46,480
"A Midsummer Night's Dream."

908
00:34:46,520 --> 00:34:47,680
Why don't you pop along?

909
00:34:47,720 --> 00:34:49,320
We'll see if we can fit you in?

910
00:34:49,360 --> 00:34:50,320
Oh, I don't know.

911
00:34:50,360 --> 00:34:51,600
I'm not much of an actress.

912
00:34:51,640 --> 00:34:53,200
Neither is Sydney Clarke.

913
00:34:53,240 --> 00:34:55,520
Never stopped her.

914
00:34:55,560 --> 00:34:56,920
I'll be there.

915
00:34:56,960 --> 00:34:58,560
I'm going to
audition, too, and maybe

916
00:34:58,600 --> 00:35:01,320
this year I'll get something.

917
00:35:01,360 --> 00:35:02,240
We'll see you later, Cheryl.

918
00:35:02,280 --> 00:35:03,080
Don't wait up.

919
00:35:08,880 --> 00:35:10,400
I'm very impressed.

920
00:35:10,440 --> 00:35:11,400
You should be.

921
00:35:11,440 --> 00:35:12,960
It's a highly skilled operation.

922
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:14,360
I just can't tell whether
you know what you're doing,

923
00:35:14,400 --> 00:35:17,000
or you're the best con
artist I've ever seen.

924
00:35:17,040 --> 00:35:18,920
If the con is done
well enough, who's to say

925
00:35:18,960 --> 00:35:20,040
it isn't the truth?

926
00:35:20,080 --> 00:35:21,280
And what if you
don't pull it off?

927
00:35:21,320 --> 00:35:23,360
The spell was broken.

928
00:35:23,400 --> 00:35:25,080
We're having a conversation,
and I don't know what

929
00:35:25,120 --> 00:35:26,480
the hell we're talking about.

930
00:35:26,520 --> 00:35:28,160
You're driving me crazy.

931
00:35:28,200 --> 00:35:29,440
I have to check the trout.

932
00:35:29,480 --> 00:35:31,920
No, wait, the trout is fine.

933
00:35:31,960 --> 00:35:35,320
I have never seen such
beautiful brown eyes in my life.

934
00:35:35,360 --> 00:35:36,720
On me, or the trout?

935
00:35:36,760 --> 00:35:40,160
Speaking of the
trout, watch out.

936
00:35:40,200 --> 00:35:43,280
All right.

937
00:35:43,320 --> 00:35:46,600
Ooh-la-la.

938
00:35:46,640 --> 00:35:48,000
All right, very good.

939
00:35:48,040 --> 00:35:49,560
Hey, a bit of cognac.

940
00:35:49,600 --> 00:35:53,080
For medicinal purposes?

941
00:35:53,120 --> 00:35:54,080
And voila!

942
00:35:54,120 --> 00:35:57,400
Oh, here we go.

943
00:35:57,440 --> 00:35:58,440
[coughing]

944
00:35:58,480 --> 00:35:59,280
Oh!

945
00:36:01,920 --> 00:36:04,000
Is this what's
supposed to happen?

946
00:36:04,040 --> 00:36:05,000
Oh!

947
00:36:05,040 --> 00:36:06,560
Oh, yeah, that's much better.

948
00:36:06,600 --> 00:36:08,880
You are the worst.

949
00:36:08,920 --> 00:36:10,680
What, you never
had a smoked trout?

950
00:36:10,720 --> 00:36:12,320
Oh, my god.

951
00:36:12,360 --> 00:36:13,600
You OK?

952
00:36:13,640 --> 00:36:14,520
I'm fine.

953
00:36:14,560 --> 00:36:15,520
Really.

954
00:36:15,560 --> 00:36:19,480
A little humiliated, but fine.

955
00:36:19,520 --> 00:36:21,200
I'm sorry about the trout.

956
00:36:21,240 --> 00:36:24,960
I know you two were just
starting to hit it off.

957
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:27,000
I just feel lucky we're alive.

958
00:36:27,040 --> 00:36:28,960
I still have my home.

959
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:30,680
Not worried about the trout.

960
00:36:30,720 --> 00:36:32,040
You like fudge?

961
00:36:32,080 --> 00:36:33,520
Love fudge.

962
00:36:33,560 --> 00:36:34,800
Do you have fudge?

963
00:36:34,840 --> 00:36:36,080
Do I have fudge?

964
00:36:36,120 --> 00:36:37,600
I made this.

965
00:36:37,640 --> 00:36:38,960
It happens to be the only
thing I know how to cook.

966
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:40,280
Is it good?

967
00:36:40,320 --> 00:36:41,440
Well, it beats the
hell out of your trout.

968
00:36:41,480 --> 00:36:42,840
Wouldn't be hard.

969
00:36:42,880 --> 00:36:44,200
Mm-hmm.

970
00:36:44,240 --> 00:36:46,160
Your fish tank's not healthy.

971
00:36:46,200 --> 00:36:47,680
- Really?
- Yep.

972
00:36:47,720 --> 00:36:49,120
Bringing up the fish tank
at this particular moment

973
00:36:49,160 --> 00:36:52,960
is, uh, slightly frustrating.

974
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:55,200
Well, I think we
hardly know each other,

975
00:36:55,240 --> 00:36:56,520
and I don't fool around
on the first date.

976
00:36:59,080 --> 00:37:00,200
Well, it's early.

977
00:37:00,240 --> 00:37:01,160
Come on, let's have
our second date.

978
00:37:01,200 --> 00:37:01,960
Come on.

979
00:37:07,440 --> 00:37:10,000
You really love
this town, don't you?

980
00:37:10,040 --> 00:37:12,120
Well, I grew up here.

981
00:37:12,160 --> 00:37:14,800
There's four generations
of Camerons buried here.

982
00:37:14,840 --> 00:37:18,120
My mother and father
are right over there.

983
00:37:18,160 --> 00:37:19,920
You loved them, too, huh?

984
00:37:19,960 --> 00:37:21,840
My parents?

985
00:37:21,880 --> 00:37:23,800
Yeah, well, they
were my parents.

986
00:37:23,840 --> 00:37:26,920
What, you don't have warm
feelings about Pushmata--

987
00:37:26,960 --> 00:37:27,800
hari?

988
00:37:27,840 --> 00:37:29,200
Pushmataha.

989
00:37:29,240 --> 00:37:30,920
Would you guys give me a break?

990
00:37:30,960 --> 00:37:32,800
Just because you live
in cliche-ville Lincoln.

991
00:37:32,840 --> 00:37:33,960
Jeez.

992
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:36,600
Pushmawhatchacallit
was wonderful.

993
00:37:36,640 --> 00:37:38,160
I loved it.

994
00:37:38,200 --> 00:37:39,920
I can't say the same thing
about my father, unfortunately.

995
00:37:39,960 --> 00:37:41,840
He left when I was nine.

996
00:37:41,880 --> 00:37:45,440
Hmm, I guess I lived
the American dream.

997
00:37:45,480 --> 00:37:47,320
You know what's
great about you, Ben?

998
00:37:47,360 --> 00:37:48,600
Yeah.

999
00:37:48,640 --> 00:37:51,280
My broad shoulders
and irresistible grin?

1000
00:37:51,320 --> 00:37:52,800
No.

1001
00:37:52,840 --> 00:37:54,360
You are who you are.

1002
00:37:54,400 --> 00:37:58,040
Rock solid, genuine,
straight forward.

1003
00:37:58,080 --> 00:37:59,080
That sounds so boring.

1004
00:38:01,800 --> 00:38:02,800
You know what I like about you?

1005
00:38:02,840 --> 00:38:04,240
It's just the opposite.

1006
00:38:04,280 --> 00:38:07,360
See, I-- I look at you
and I see something more.

1007
00:38:07,400 --> 00:38:09,360
I know there's something more.

1008
00:38:09,400 --> 00:38:11,400
You got me curious.

1009
00:38:11,440 --> 00:38:15,120
Is that something new for you,
a woman who makes you curious?

1010
00:38:15,160 --> 00:38:17,120
Well, maybe there was one or
two when I lived in New York.

1011
00:38:17,160 --> 00:38:18,240
You lived in New York?

1012
00:38:18,280 --> 00:38:19,120
Yeah.

1013
00:38:19,160 --> 00:38:20,080
You surprised?

1014
00:38:20,120 --> 00:38:21,160
Yeah, I am a little.

1015
00:38:24,520 --> 00:38:26,040
You didn't like the big city?

1016
00:38:26,080 --> 00:38:27,320
No, it was all right.

1017
00:38:27,360 --> 00:38:29,800
I just moved back
when I had the chance.

1018
00:38:29,840 --> 00:38:32,440
Never really felt
right anywhere else.

1019
00:38:32,480 --> 00:38:34,280
Whoa, do you see
that falling star?

1020
00:38:34,320 --> 00:38:36,800
Oh, yeah, you don't
see those too often.

1021
00:38:36,840 --> 00:38:41,040
Where I come from, you
see them all the time.

1022
00:38:41,080 --> 00:38:42,360
You cold?

1023
00:38:42,400 --> 00:38:44,560
Yeah, I am a little bit.

1024
00:38:44,600 --> 00:38:45,880
Thank you.

1025
00:38:45,920 --> 00:38:48,840
So uh, what's your
policy on third dates?

1026
00:38:48,880 --> 00:38:49,760
Hi.

1027
00:38:49,800 --> 00:38:52,200
Two, please.

1028
00:38:52,240 --> 00:38:53,600
Enjoy the show.

1029
00:38:53,640 --> 00:38:55,280
Yep.

1030
00:38:55,320 --> 00:38:56,800
You want anything to eat?

1031
00:38:56,840 --> 00:38:57,800
No, I'm OK right now.

1032
00:38:57,840 --> 00:38:58,640
OK.

1033
00:39:04,640 --> 00:39:06,400
Let's sit up on the stage.

1034
00:39:06,440 --> 00:39:10,280
No, I like to sit
right in the middle.

1035
00:39:10,320 --> 00:39:11,360
Right here.

1036
00:39:11,400 --> 00:39:15,320
Wow, such a control freak.

1037
00:39:15,360 --> 00:39:16,160
Ah.

1038
00:39:20,040 --> 00:39:21,320
What are you so happy about?

1039
00:39:21,360 --> 00:39:23,120
Oh, I love this.

1040
00:39:23,160 --> 00:39:25,440
It's just a movie theater.

1041
00:39:25,480 --> 00:39:29,360
Ordinary and wonderful.

1042
00:39:29,400 --> 00:39:30,560
Oh, well, you
know, if it makes

1043
00:39:30,600 --> 00:39:31,640
you so happy going
to the movies,

1044
00:39:31,680 --> 00:39:33,480
we should do it more often.

1045
00:39:33,520 --> 00:39:35,480
I think this date is
going really well.

1046
00:39:35,520 --> 00:39:36,640
I'm having fun.
So am I.

1047
00:39:36,680 --> 00:39:37,840
NARRATOR [ON FILM]:
Now, in the role

1048
00:39:37,880 --> 00:39:38,960
you've been waiting
for her to play--

1049
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:40,280
Frankly, I need some help.

1050
00:39:40,320 --> 00:39:41,480
NARRATOR [ON FILM]:
--Sydney Clarke.

1051
00:39:41,520 --> 00:39:43,600
I need someone
who knows the game,

1052
00:39:43,640 --> 00:39:45,040
and can point the way for me.

1053
00:39:45,080 --> 00:39:46,920
NARRATOR [ON FILM]: Sydney
Clarke, more beautiful

1054
00:39:46,960 --> 00:39:48,800
and more dangerous than ever.

1055
00:39:48,840 --> 00:39:50,000
SYDNEY CLARKE, AS CHERYL
BELSON [VOICEOVER]: If the con

1056
00:39:50,040 --> 00:39:51,320
is done well enough--
- Oh, my god.

1057
00:39:51,360 --> 00:39:52,440
SYDNEY CLARKE, AS CHERYL
BELSON [VOICEOVER]:

1058
00:39:52,480 --> 00:39:53,680
--who's to say it
isn't the truth?

1059
00:39:53,720 --> 00:39:54,960
I could use a real
friend right now.

1060
00:39:55,000 --> 00:39:55,800
And I know that I
can't just ask you to--

1061
00:39:55,840 --> 00:39:57,080
You're--

1062
00:39:57,120 --> 00:39:58,680
--drop everything
and run up here, but.

1063
00:39:58,720 --> 00:40:02,120
NARRATOR [ON FILM]: First,
you see her, then you don't.

1064
00:40:02,160 --> 00:40:03,960
And what happens in
between will have

1065
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:05,680
you screaming bloody murder.

1066
00:40:05,720 --> 00:40:07,360
Ben.

1067
00:40:07,400 --> 00:40:09,240
NARRATOR [ON FILM]: No matter
how many nightmares you've had,

1068
00:40:09,280 --> 00:40:11,600
you'll never have
ones like this.

1069
00:40:11,640 --> 00:40:12,800
Ben.

1070
00:40:12,840 --> 00:40:13,840
Well, I guess the
joke's on me, huh?

1071
00:40:13,880 --> 00:40:15,040
- Ben, come on.
- Wow.

1072
00:40:15,080 --> 00:40:16,400
Am I going to make
the fan mags now?

1073
00:40:16,440 --> 00:40:18,000
- Let me explain at least.
- No, you got me.

1074
00:40:18,040 --> 00:40:18,920
That was a good one.

1075
00:40:18,960 --> 00:40:20,200
I mean, you really--

